B.P4=s(["Okay, real quick \u2014","Sure thing.","Easy one.","Alright, here's the deal:","Good question.","Let's break it down.","So, check it:","Right, listen:","Happy to help.","Here you go:","No problem at all.","Cool, so:","Gotcha.","Simple version:","Love this one.","Quick rundown:","Here's how it works:","Let me hit you with it:","Say less.","Oh, that's a fun one.","Alright alright:","Boom, here:"],t.s)
B.P6=s([0,0.58,1],t.n)
B.PU=s(["Slide a coloured block into the gate that matches its colour \u2014 line up the lane so it can slip out. Clear the whole board to beat the level.","It's all about matching: drag each block to the gate of the same colour. When their lanes line up, the block exits. Empty the board and you're through.","Every block wants a gate its own colour. Slide it so its row or column lines up with that gate, and out it goes. Do that for all of them to clear the level.","Match colours, clear blocks. Push a block into the same-colour gate (lanes have to line up), and repeat until the board's empty.","Think of gates as colour-coded doors. Slide each block to the matching door with the lanes aligned, and it leaves. Clear them all to beat the level.","Drag blocks to the gate that shares their colour. Line up the lane first, then it exits. Board empty equals level done.","The goal's simple: get every block out through its matching-colour gate. Slide to line up the lanes, and they pop right out.","Colour to colour, that's the game. Move a block until it lines up with its same-colour gate, and it clears. Do the whole board to advance.","Slide, match, clear. Each block exits through the gate of its own colour once the lanes agree. Clear the board and onward you go.","You're guiding blocks home: each one leaves through the gate matching its colour. Line up the lane, watch it go, repeat till the board's clear."],t.s)
B.Tm=new A.iE("How do I play?",B.mx,B.PU)
B.Mj=new A.b0(63666,"MaterialIcons",!1)
B.Q4=s(["Gates are the coloured openings around the board's edge. A block only escapes through a gate that matches its colour, and only when their lanes line up.","Those coloured slots on the edges? Gates. Each one only lets out blocks of its own colour, once the lane's aligned.","A gate's basically a colour-locked exit. Match the block's colour to the gate and line up the row or column, then it slides out.","Gates sit on the board's borders, each with a colour. Send a block to the same-colour gate with lanes lined up and it's gone.","Every gate has a colour, and it's picky: only same-colour blocks get through, and only when the lane matches up.","See the coloured openings on the edges? A block leaves through the one matching its colour. Line up the lane and it exits.","Gates are exits with a colour rule. Get a block to its matching gate, align the lane, done.","Think colour-coded doors on the board's rim. A block uses the door of its colour, and lanes have to agree first.","Gates only open for their own colour. Slide a block into the matching gate with the lane lined up and out it pops.","They're the edge openings you clear blocks through, each keyed to one colour. Same colour plus a lined-up lane equals exit."],t.s)
B.Ts=new A.iE("What are gates?",B.Mj,B.Q4)
B.Qz=s(["Steel blocks are the cool-grey ones, and they do not budge. Think of them as walls and route your other blocks around them.","The grey metal blocks? Bolted down. You can't move steel at all, so treat it like a wall and plan around it.","Steel equals immovable. It just sits there being grey and stubborn, so work your movable blocks around it.","Those grey blocks won't slide no matter what. They're obstacles: use them as fixed points and steer everything else past.","Steel blocks are the walls of the puzzle. They never move, so the trick is finding paths around them.","Can't move it? That's steel. Grey, solid, permanent. Plan your slides so nothing needs to go through it.","Steel's the one block that ignores you completely, it's fixed. Treat it as scenery and route around.","The grey ones are steel: total walls. No sliding them, so weave your other blocks around instead.","Steel blocks don't take orders. They stay put as obstacles, and your job is getting past them, not through them.","Grey and going nowhere, that's steel. Use it as a wall and thread your other blocks around it."],t.s)
B.Tn=new A.iE("Steel blocks?",B.qT,B.Qz)
B.Pr=s(["Rail blocks slide on one axis only, so check the little arrows. Horizontal rails go left and right, vertical ones go up and down.","See the arrows on a block? That's a rail. It only moves along that one line: left-right or up-down, never both.","Rails are stuck on a track. The arrows tell you which way: a horizontal rail slides side to side, a vertical one slides up and down.","A rail block picks a lane and commits, one axis, shown by its arrows. Plan around the fact it can't turn.","Rails only travel one direction-pair. Arrows point the way: horizontal is left-right, vertical is up-down, no cross-moves.","Those arrow blocks are rails, single-axis movers. Follow the arrows and you'll know if it's a left-right or up-down piece.","Rail equals one-track mind. It slides along its arrows only, so a horizontal rail won't ever go vertical.","Check the arrows: rails move on just one axis. Horizontal ones roll sideways, vertical ones roll up and down.","A rail block can only go the way its arrows point, one axis. Great for lining up, tricky if you need the other direction.","Rails ride a single line. Arrows are the allowed direction: horizontal slides left-right, vertical slides up-down, and that's your lot."],t.s)
B.Tk=new A.iE("Rail blocks?",B.r0,B.Pr)
B.RC=s(["Gems are the glowing diamonds on the board. Slide a block through one to sweep it up for bonus points and lifetime rank.","Those sparkly diamonds? Free points. Run a block over a gem to grab it, great to snag on your way to a gate.","Gems equal bonus. Sweep them by moving a block across them; they pad your score and your lifetime gem rank.","See a diamond glinting? Slide a block through it to collect. Gems boost your points and your rank over time.","Gems are little score bonuses sitting on the board. Sweep one with a block as you go, no reason to leave them behind.","Grab gems by sliding a block over them. Each one's extra points and counts toward your all-time gem total.","The glowing diamonds are gems. Collect them by passing a block through: bonus points plus rank, easy pickings.","Gems reward good pathing. Route a block through a diamond to sweep it for extra score on the way to clearing.","Those diamonds are worth grabbing. Slide a block across to sweep the gem: points now, rank later.","Gems are the shiny bonuses. Move a block over one to collect it; they stack up for score and lifetime rank."],t.s)
B.Tl=new A.iE("What are gems?",B.jb,B.RC)
B.Mh=new A.b0(63578,"MaterialIcons",!1)
B.QZ=s(["Clear blocks quickly one after another and they chain, so each clear scores higher than the last. Watch the combo meter and keep the streak alive.","Combos are all about speed: clear one block, then another right after, and the multiplier climbs. Don't let the meter run out.","A chain is back-to-back clears. String them together fast and each link's worth more; the combo meter tracks your streak.","Rapid-fire clears build a chain, and the chain builds your multiplier. The quicker the next clear, the bigger the score.","Keep clearing without pausing and you'll start a combo, where every consecutive clear multiplies harder. The meter shows how hot you are.","Combos love momentum. Clear, clear, clear in quick succession and the multiplier stacks; let the meter empty and the chain's gone.","The trick to big scores is chaining your clears. Each one soon after the last raises the multiplier, and the combo meter is your timer.","Clear blocks in a tight streak to chain them. More links means a fatter multiplier, so mind the meter before it resets.","A chain is just quick consecutive clears, and it snowballs your score. Watch the combo meter and keep feeding it.","Speed makes combos: line up your clears so they happen fast, and the multiplier keeps climbing until the meter drops."],t.s)
B.Tq=new A.iE("Combos & chains",B.Mh,B.QZ)
B.R3=s(["Seven modes, each its own vibe: Normal (relaxed), Timer (a 10:00 attack), Run (survive the clock), Extreme (big hard boards), Endless (keeps ramping), Cascade (place pieces, clear lines), and Nightmare (brutal, unlocks at Level 8).","Here's the lineup: Normal for chilling, Timer for a 10-minute sprint, Run to survive on a ticking clock, Extreme for hard-from-the-start, Endless that never eases up, Cascade for line-clearing, and Nightmare if you're feeling brave at Level 8.","Modes: Normal is the calm classic; Timer gives you 10:00; Run banks seconds as you clear; Extreme goes big and hard immediately; Endless escalates forever; Cascade is place-and-clear-lines; Nightmare is pure survival, unlocked at Level 8.","You've got Normal (easy-going), Timer (beat 10:00), Run (clock survival), Extreme (large tough boards), Endless (ever-harder), Cascade (a different line-clear puzzle), and Nightmare (savage, a Level 8 unlock).","Quick tour: Normal is relaxed, Timer is 10 minutes flat, Run is survive by banking time, Extreme is hard from level one, Endless is an infinite ramp, Cascade is drop pieces to clear lines, Nightmare is brutal and needs Level 8.","Seven of them. Normal to learn, Timer for time-attack, Run for survival, Extreme for a challenge off the bat, Endless for the long haul, Cascade for a line-clearing twist, and Nightmare for the truly bold at Level 8.","The modes range from chill to chaos: Normal, Timer (10:00), Run (bank seconds to survive), Extreme (big and hard), Endless (climbing difficulty), Cascade (place pieces, clear lines), and Nightmare (unlocks at Level 8, and it's mean).","Pick your mood: Normal (calm), Timer (race the 10:00 clock), Run (survive it), Extreme (no easing in), Endless (forever harder), Cascade (line clears), or Nightmare (Level 8, and it does not play nice).","There are seven. Normal and Cascade are the relaxed pair, Cascade being a place-pieces line game; Timer and Run are the clock ones; Extreme and Endless crank difficulty; Nightmare is the boss of them all at Level 8.","Rundown: Normal (relaxed), Timer (10:00 time attack), Run (survival, bank seconds per clear), Extreme (big hard boards immediately), Endless (never stops ramping), Cascade (place pieces to clear lines), and Nightmare (brutal, opens at Level 8)."],t.s)
B.Tr=new A.iE("Explain the modes",B.hd,B.R3)
B.Mz=new A.b0(983636,"MaterialIcons",!0)
B.PZ=s(["You earn XP by clearing levels, chaining combos, and sweeping gems. Level up and you get gems plus new unlocks; Nightmare opens at Level 8. Check the Profile tab for your progress.","Every clear, combo, and gem feeds your XP. Hit a new level for a gem reward and fresh unlocks (like Nightmare at Level 8). Your Profile tab shows it all.","Leveling's automatic: play and your XP climbs from clears, combos, and gems. New levels drop gems and open modes, with Nightmare as the Level 8 milestone.","XP comes from playing: clearing boards, chaining, grabbing gems. Each level-up pays gems and can unlock a mode (Nightmare needs Level 8). Peek at the Profile tab.","Rack up XP through clears, combos, and gem sweeps. Leveling grants gems and unlocks, the big one being Nightmare at Level 8. It's all on your Profile.","Play, earn XP, level up. Levels hand you gems and unlock content; Nightmare specifically wants you at Level 8. Track it on the Profile tab.","Your level rises as you clear levels, build combos, and collect gems. Rewards are gems plus unlocks, and Nightmare is gated to Level 8.","Leveling up means gems in your pocket and new modes on the menu. You gain XP just by playing well, and Nightmare unlocks once you reach Level 8.","XP is earned from clears, chains, and gems. Cross a level and you're rewarded with gems and unlocks; Nightmare arrives at Level 8. See Profile for details.","Keep playing and you'll level up naturally. Each level brings gems and can unlock a mode; the headline unlock, Nightmare, needs Level 8."],t.s)
B.Tj=new A.iE("Leveling & unlocks",B.Mz,B.PZ)
B.P9=s(["Come back each day to claim a gem reward. The streak escalates over a 7-day cycle, so day 7 is the jackpot. There's a daily challenge too, and both live on the Home tab.","Daily rewards climb: claim once a day and the payout grows across a 7-day loop, peaking on day 7. Plus a daily challenge for extra gems, all on Home.","Log in daily for gems. The streak ramps up over seven days, and day 7 pays the most. Don't skip the daily challenge either; find them on the Home tab.","Each day you can grab an escalating gem reward (a 7-day cycle, day 7's the big one). A separate daily challenge tops it up, all on Home.","Show up daily and the gem reward gets bigger through the week, with day 7 as the payoff. There's also a challenge for bonus gems, both on the Home tab.","Daily gems escalate over a 7-day streak, so keep the run going for that day-7 jackpot. The daily challenge adds even more; check Home.","The daily reward grows each day across a week-long cycle (biggest on day 7). Pair it with the daily challenge for extra gems; the Home tab has both.","Claim daily for a gem reward that climbs over 7 days, jackpotting on day 7. And knock out the daily challenge while you're at it, all on Home.","There's a daily gem reward that escalates on a 7-day loop (day 7 is the sweet spot), plus a daily challenge. Grab them from the Home tab.","Daily login equals gems, and the amount ramps up over a 7-day streak (day 7 is the jackpot). The daily challenge gives more. Both are on Home."],t.s)
B.To=new A.iE("Daily rewards",B.qV,B.P9)
B.PM=s(["Chase combos, because chaining fast clears is where the big points hide. Sweep gems on the way, and in escalating modes, surviving deeper multiplies your score.","For a high score: keep your clears fast and chained, grab every gem you pass, and don't waste moves. Momentum beats caution.","Points love speed. Plan a few moves ahead so you can clear in quick succession for combos, and never skip a gem you can sweep.","Top scores come from chaining. Line up multiple clears so they fire back-to-back, collect gems en route, and push deeper in modes that reward it.","Tip: think in chains, not single clears. Set up blocks so one clear leads into the next, and pick up gems along the path.","Big scores mean combos plus gems plus survival. Keep the combo meter fed, sweep diamonds, and in Endless or Nightmare, lasting longer means bigger multipliers.","Plan your paths so clears stack into a chain; that multiplier is the whole game at high level. Gems are easy bonus points too.","Want a leaderboard run? Prioritise chained clears, snag gems without detouring much, and in ramping modes remember that depth is score.","Score smarter: line up combos in advance, sweep gems as you move, and avoid wasted slides. Efficiency and chains win.","Here's the meta: combos multiply, gems add up, and surviving deeper in the harder modes scales your points. Chain everything you can."],t.s)
B.Tp=new A.iE("High-score tips",B.qW,B.PM)
